<paragraph id="1B57055C1002A15D03E3FD9AFA3AFDD9" blockId="19.[151,1436,548,611]" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">
The members of this species group are characterized by their body length not exceeding 
<quantity id="DC10A8B91002A15D07F0FD9BFB7BFD85" box="[1156,1243,548,575]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="19" pageNumber="220" unit="mm" value="8.5">8.5 mm</quantity>
and the shape of male tergum 7, which is bifid bearing two short spines or two teeth of rectangular to triangular shape (
<figureCitation id="83D319D91002A15D067BFDF6FA2DFDD9" box="[1295,1421,585,611]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–23" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1446,1471]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,181,1421]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,181,1421]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 15–23: Osmia (Tergosmia). 15: Female of O. tergestensis in front of her brood cell hidden in a rock fissure (photo A. Krebs). 16: Female of O. tergestensis folding petal after having it bitten off from flower of Geranium pyrenaicum (Geraniaceae; photo A. Krebs). 17: Brood cells of O. tergestensis between blades of dense grass tussock. 18: Brood cell of O. avosetta at the end of a short burrow in the ground (photo C. Sedivy). 19: Female of O. lunata depositing nectar in her brood cell built in a short burrow in the ground. 20–22: Male terga 6–7 of O. avosetta (20), O. lunata (21), O. rhodoensis (22) and O. tergestensis (23)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3826177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3826177/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="220">Fig. 22, 23</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
